'''Györgyi Balogh''' (born 1 May 1948) is a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] former [[sprint (running)|sprinter]]. She placed second in women's [[200 metres]] at the [[1971 European Athletics Championships|1971 European Championships]] in [[Helsinki]] and competed in the [[Summer Olympic Games]] in [[1968 Summer Olympics|1968]] and [[1972 Summer Olympics|1972]].

==Career==

At the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Summer Olympics]] in [[Mexico City]] Balogh competed in the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metres|100 metres]], [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics – Women's 200 metres|200 metres]] and the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 100 metres relay|4 × 100 metres relay]],<ref name="sr">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/gyorgyi-balogh-szomov-1.html |title=Györgyi Balogh-Szomov Bio, Stats and Results |accessdate=30 April 2014 |publisher=Sports Reference LLC}}</ref> only qualifying from the first round in the [[100 metres]], in which she was eliminated in the second round.<ref name="sr"/>

Balogh also competed in the [[1969 European Athletics Championships|1969 European Championships]] in [[Athens]] without much more success,<ref name="tp">{{tilastopaja|id=42151|sex=w}}</ref> but [[1971 European Athletics Championships|two years later]] in [[Helsinki]] she won the silver at 200 metres, running 23.26 and losing only to [[East Germany]]'s [[Renate Stecher]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/ecw.htm |title=European Championships (Women) |publisher=''[[Athletics Weekly]]'' |accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> In addition, she placed fifth in both the 100 metres and the [[4 × 100 metres relay]].<ref name="tp"/>

She returned to the Olympics in [[Athletics at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972 Summer Olympics]], this time running the [[400 metres]].<ref name="sr"/> She led the quarter-finals with a time of 51.71, which was her personal best and briefly an [[List of Olympic records in athletics|Olympic record]].<ref name="sr"/> In the semi-finals she ran 51.90 and qualified for the final, in which she placed eighth and last in 52.39; her quarter-final time would have been enough.for fourth place.<ref name="sr"/>

Representing the [[Budapest]] club [[Vasas SC]], Balogh won Hungarian championships in the 100 m (1968, 1971 and 1972), 200 m (1968–1972), 400 m (1971 and 1972), 4&nbsp;×&nbsp;100 m (1969–1972 and 1975), 4&nbsp;×&nbsp;200 m (1969–1971 and 1975), 4&nbsp;×&nbsp;400 m (1970–1972 and 1975) and [[80 m hurdles]] (1968).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kerszoft.hu/szepesi/atletika/nob.htm |title=Magyar nõi bajnokok atlétikában, szabad téren |language=Hungarian |accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> {{As of|2014}}, her personal best in the 200 metres (22.8 from 1971) is still the [[Hungarian records in athletics|Hungarian record]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.masz.hu/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=413:magyar-szabadteri-felntt-noi-rekordok&catid=61&Itemid=29 |title=Magyar szabadtéri felnőtt női rekordok |publisher=Magyar Atlétikai Szövetség |accessdate=30 April 2014 |language=Hungarian}}</ref>

